events.description: Diocletian and Maximian retire from the office of Roman emperor.
events.html: • 305 – Diocletian and Maximian retire from the office of Roman emperor.

events.description: The Nea Ekklesia is inaugurated in Constantinople, setting the model for all later cross-in-square Orthodox churches.
events.html: • 880 – The Nea Ekklesia is inaugurated in Constantinople, setting the model for all later cross-in-square Orthodox churches.

events.description: Norman mercenaries land at Bannow Bay in Leinster, marking the beginning of the Norman invasion of Ireland.
events.html: • 1169 – Norman mercenaries land at Bannow Bay in Leinster, marking the beginning of the Norman invasion of Ireland.

events.description: Wars of Scottish Independence end: By the Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton, England recognises Scotland as an independent state.
events.html: • 1328 – Wars of Scottish Independence end: By the Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton, England recognises Scotland as an independent state.

events.description: Christopher Columbus presents his plans discovering a western route to the Indies to the Spanish Queen Isabella I of Castile.
events.html: • 1486 – Christopher Columbus presents his plans discovering a western route to the Indies to the Spanish Queen Isabella I of Castile.[1]

events.description: Henry Morgan's raid on Lake Maracaibo, the Spanish Armada de Barlovento is defeated by an English Privateer fleet led by Captain Henry Morgan.
events.html: • 1669 – Henry Morgan's raid on Lake Maracaibo, the Spanish Armada de Barlovento is defeated by an English Privateer fleet led by Captain Henry Morgan.[2]

entities.name: Henry Morgan's raid on Lake Maracaibo

events.description: The Act of Union joining England and Scotland to form the Kingdom of Great Britain takes effect.
events.html: • 1707 – The Act of Union joining England and Scotland to form the Kingdom of Great Britain takes effect.[3]

events.description: Publication of Species Plantarum by Linnaeus, and the formal start date of plant taxonomy adopted by the International Code of Botanical Nomenclature.
events.html: • 1753 – Publication of Species Plantarum by Linnaeus, and the formal start date of plant taxonomy adopted by the International Code of Botanical Nomenclature.

events.description: The Slave Trade Act 1807 takes effect, abolishing the slave trade within the British Empire.
events.html: • 1807 – The Slave Trade Act 1807 takes effect, abolishing the slave trade within the British Empire.[4]

events.description: Execution of the Cato Street Conspirators, who plotted to kill the British Cabinet and Prime Minister Lord Liverpool.
events.html: • 1820 – Execution of the Cato Street Conspirators, who plotted to kill the British Cabinet and Prime Minister Lord Liverpool.[5]

entities.name: Prime Minister of the United Kingdom

events.description: The Penny Black, the first official adhesive postage stamp, is issued in the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1840 – The Penny Black, the first official adhesive postage stamp, is issued in the United Kingdom.

events.description: Hong Kong Police Force, the world's second modern police force and Asia's first, is established.
events.html: • 1844 – Hong Kong Police Force, the world's second modern police force and Asia's first, is established.

events.description: The few remaining Mormons left in Nauvoo, Illinois, formally dedicate the Nauvoo Temple.
events.html: • 1846 – The few remaining Mormons left in Nauvoo, Illinois, formally dedicate the Nauvoo Temple.

events.description: Queen Victoria opens The Great Exhibition at The Crystal Palace in London.
events.html: • 1851 – Queen Victoria opens The Great Exhibition at The Crystal Palace in London.

events.description: American Civil War: The Battle of Chancellorsville between Robert E. Lee's Confederate Army of Northern Virginia and the Union Army of the Potomac under Joseph Hooker begins.
events.html: • 1863 – American Civil War: The Battle of Chancellorsville between Robert E. Lee's Confederate Army of Northern Virginia and the Union Army of the Potomac under Joseph Hooker begins.[6]

events.description: American Civil War: During the Vicksburg campaign, Union forces under Ulysses S. Grant win at the Battle of Port Gibson and establish a firm presence on the east side of the Mississippi River.
events.html: • 1863 – American Civil War: During the Vicksburg campaign, Union forces under Ulysses S. Grant win at the Battle of Port Gibson and establish a firm presence on the east side of the Mississippi River.[7]

events.description: The Empire of Brazil, Argentina, and Uruguay sign the Treaty of the Triple Alliance.
events.html: • 1865 – The Empire of Brazil, Argentina, and Uruguay sign the Treaty of the Triple Alliance.

events.description: The Memphis Race Riots begin. Over three days, 46 blacks and two whites were killed. Reports of the atrocities influenced passage of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.
events.html: • 1866 – The Memphis Race Riots begin. Over three days, 46 blacks and two whites were killed. Reports of the atrocities influenced passage of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.[8]

entities.name: Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution

events.description: The original Chicago Board of Trade Building opens for business.
events.html: • 1885 – The original Chicago Board of Trade Building opens for business.

events.description: Rallies are held throughout the United States demanding the eight-hour work day, culminating in the Haymarket affair in Chicago, in commemoration of which May 1 is celebrated as International Workers' Day in many countries.
events.html: • 1886 – Rallies are held throughout the United States demanding the eight-hour work day, culminating in the Haymarket affair in Chicago, in commemoration of which May 1 is celebrated as International Workers' Day in many countries.

events.description: Coxey's Army, the first significant American protest march, arrives in Washington, D.C.
events.html: • 1894 – Coxey's Army, the first significant American protest march, arrives in Washington, D.C.[9]

events.description: Naser al-Din, Shah of Iran, is assassinated in Shah Abdol-Azim Shrine by Mirza Reza Kermani, a follower of Jamal al-Din al-Afghani.
events.html: • 1896 – Naser al-Din, Shah of Iran, is assassinated in Shah Abdol-Azim Shrine by Mirza Reza Kermani, a follower of Jamal al-Din al-Afghani.[10]

events.description: Spanish–American War: Battle of Manila Bay: The Asiatic Squadron of the United States Navy destroys the Pacific Squadron of the Spanish Navy after a seven-hour battle. Spain loses all seven of its ships, and 381 Spanish sailors die. There are no American vessel losses or combat deaths.
events.html: • 1898 – Spanish–American War: Battle of Manila Bay: The Asiatic Squadron of the United States Navy destroys the Pacific Squadron of the Spanish Navy after a seven-hour battle. Spain loses all seven of its ships, and 381 Spanish sailors die. There are no American vessel losses or combat deaths.[11]

events.description: The Scofield Mine disaster kills over 200 men in Scofield, Utah in what is to date the fifth-worst mining accident in United States history.
events.html: • 1900 – The Scofield Mine disaster kills over 200 men in Scofield, Utah in what is to date the fifth-worst mining accident in United States history.

events.description: RMS Lusitania departs from New York City on her 202nd, and final, crossing of the North Atlantic. Six days later, the ship is torpedoed off the coast of Ireland with the loss of 1,198 lives.
events.html: • 1915 – RMS Lusitania departs from New York City on her 202nd, and final, crossing of the North Atlantic. Six days later, the ship is torpedoed off the coast of Ireland with the loss of 1,198 lives.

events.description: German troops enter Munich to suppress the Bavarian Soviet Republic.
events.html: • 1919 – German troops enter Munich to suppress the Bavarian Soviet Republic.

events.description: The Jaffa riots commence.
events.html: • 1921 – The Jaffa riots commence.[12]

events.description: The All-China Federation of Trade Unions is officially founded. Today it is the largest trade union in the world, with 134 million members.
events.html: • 1925 – The All-China Federation of Trade Unions is officially founded. Today it is the largest trade union in the world, with 134 million members.

events.description: The 7.2 Mw  Kopet Dag earthquake shakes the Iran–Turkmenistan border region with a maximum Mercalli intensity of IX (Violent), killing up to 3,800 and injuring 1,121.
events.html: • 1929 – The 7.2 Mw  Kopet Dag earthquake shakes the Iran–Turkmenistan border region with a maximum Mercalli intensity of IX (Violent), killing up to 3,800 and injuring 1,121.

events.description: "Pluto" is officially proposed for the name of the newly discovered dwarf planet by Vesto Slipher in the Lowell Observatory Observation Circular. The name quickly catches on.
events.html: • 1930 – "Pluto" is officially proposed for the name of the newly discovered dwarf planet by Vesto Slipher in the Lowell Observatory Observation Circular. The name quickly catches on.[13]

events.description: The Empire State Building is dedicated in New York City.
events.html: • 1931 – The Empire State Building is dedicated in New York City.

events.description: World War II: German radio broadcasts news of Adolf Hitler's death, falsely stating that he has "fallen at his command post in the Reich Chancellery fighting to the last breath against Bolshevism and for Germany". The Soviet flag is raised over the Reich Chancellery, by order of Stalin.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: German radio broadcasts news of Adolf Hitler's death, falsely stating that he has "fallen at his command post in the Reich Chancellery fighting to the last breath against Bolshevism and for Germany". The Soviet flag is raised over the Reich Chancellery, by order of Stalin.

events.description: World War II: Up to 2,500 people die in a mass suicide in Demmin following the advance of the Red Army.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: Up to 2,500 people die in a mass suicide in Demmin following the advance of the Red Army.

events.description: Start of three-year Pilbara strike of Indigenous Australians.
events.html: • 1946 – Start of three-year Pilbara strike of Indigenous Australians.

events.description: Portella della Ginestra massacre against May Day celebrations in Sicily by the bandit and separatist leader Salvatore Giuliano where 11 persons are killed and 33 wounded.
events.html: • 1947 – Portella della Ginestra massacre against May Day celebrations in Sicily by the bandit and separatist leader Salvatore Giuliano where 11 persons are killed and 33 wounded.

events.description: The polio vaccine developed by Jonas Salk is made available to the public.
events.html: • 1956 – The polio vaccine developed by Jonas Salk is made available to the public.

events.description: A Vickers VC.1 Viking crashes while attempting to return to Blackbushe Airport in Yateley, killing 34.
events.html: • 1957 – A Vickers VC.1 Viking crashes while attempting to return to Blackbushe Airport in Yateley, killing 34.[14]

events.description: Cold War: U-2 incident: Francis Gary Powers, in a Lockheed U-2 spyplane, is shot down over the Sverdlovsk Oblast, Soviet Union, sparking a diplomatic crisis.
events.html: • 1960 – Cold War: U-2 incident: Francis Gary Powers, in a Lockheed U-2 spyplane, is shot down over the Sverdlovsk Oblast, Soviet Union, sparking a diplomatic crisis.

events.description: The Prime Minister of Cuba, Fidel Castro, proclaims Cuba a socialist nation and abolishes elections.
events.html: • 1961 – The Prime Minister of Cuba, Fidel Castro, proclaims Cuba a socialist nation and abolishes elections.

events.description: Vietnam War: Protests erupt in response to U.S. and South Vietnamese forces attacking Vietnamese communists in a Cambodian Campaign.
events.html: • 1970 – Vietnam War: Protests erupt in response to U.S. and South Vietnamese forces attacking Vietnamese communists in a Cambodian Campaign.

events.description: Amtrak (the National Railroad Passenger Corporation) takes over operation of U.S. passenger rail service.
events.html: • 1971 – Amtrak (the National Railroad Passenger Corporation) takes over operation of U.S. passenger rail service.[15]

entities.name: Rail transportation in the United States

events.description: The Särkänniemi Amusement Park opens in Tampere, Finland.
events.html: • 1975 – The Särkänniemi Amusement Park opens in Tampere, Finland.[16]

events.description: Japan's Naomi Uemura, travelling by dog sled, becomes the first person to reach the North Pole alone.
events.html: • 1978 – Japan's Naomi Uemura, travelling by dog sled, becomes the first person to reach the North Pole alone.

events.description: Operation Black Buck: The Royal Air Force attacks the Argentine Air Force during Falklands War.
events.html: • 1982 – Operation Black Buck: The Royal Air Force attacks the Argentine Air Force during Falklands War.

events.description: Angolan Civil War: The MPLA and UNITA agree to the Bicesse Accords, which are formally signed on May 31 in Lisbon.
events.html: • 1991 – Angolan Civil War: The MPLA and UNITA agree to the Bicesse Accords, which are formally signed on May 31 in Lisbon.[17][18]

events.description: Sri Lankan President Ranasinghe Premadasa is assassinated in Colombo in a suicide bombing carried out by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
events.html: • 1993 – Sri Lankan President Ranasinghe Premadasa is assassinated in Colombo in a suicide bombing carried out by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.[19]

events.description: Three-time Formula One champion Ayrton Senna is killed in an accident during the San Marino Grand Prix.
events.html: • 1994 – Three-time Formula One champion Ayrton Senna is killed in an accident during the San Marino Grand Prix.[20]

entities.name: List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions

events.description: Labour Party wins the 1997 General Election and Tony Blair is elected as Prime Minister
events.html: • 1997 – Labour Party wins the 1997 General Election and Tony Blair is elected as Prime Minister[21]

events.description: The body of British climber George Mallory is found on Mount Everest, 75 years after his disappearance in 1924.
events.html: • 1999 – The body of British climber George Mallory is found on Mount Everest, 75 years after his disappearance in 1924.[22]

events.description: Invasion of Iraq: In what becomes known as the "Mission Accomplished" speech, on board the USS Abraham Lincoln (off the coast of California), U.S. President George W. Bush declares that "major combat operations in Iraq have ended".
events.html: • 2003 – Invasion of Iraq: In what becomes known as the "Mission Accomplished" speech, on board the USS Abraham Lincoln (off the coast of California), U.S. President George W. Bush declares that "major combat operations in Iraq have ended".

events.description: Cyprus, Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia join the European Union, celebrated at the residence of the Irish President in Dublin.
events.html: • 2004 – Cyprus, Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia join the European Union, celebrated at the residence of the Irish President in Dublin.

events.description: Same-sex marriage is legalized in Sweden.
events.html: • 2009 – Same-sex marriage is legalized in Sweden.[23]

events.description: Faisal Shahzad attempts to detonate a car bomb in Times Square, but the bomb fails to go off.
events.html: • 2010 – Faisal Shahzad attempts to detonate a car bomb in Times Square, but the bomb fails to go off.[24]

events.description: Pope John Paul II is beatified by his successor, Pope Benedict XVI.
events.html: • 2011 – Pope John Paul II is beatified by his successor, Pope Benedict XVI.

events.description: Syrian civil war: The Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) resumes the Deir ez-Zor campaign in order to clear the remnants of the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) from the Iraq–Syria border.
events.html: • 2018 – Syrian civil war: The Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) resumes the Deir ez-Zor campaign in order to clear the remnants of the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) from the Iraq–Syria border.[25][26]

entities.name: Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant

events.description: Naxalite attack in Gadchiroli district of India: Sixteen army soldiers, including a driver, killed in an IED blast. Naxals targeted an anti-Naxal operations team.
events.html: • 2019 – Naxalite attack in Gadchiroli district of India: Sixteen army soldiers, including a driver, killed in an IED blast. Naxals targeted an anti-Naxal operations team.[27]

events.description: Naruhito ascends to the throne of Japan succeeding his father Akihito, beginning the Reiwa period.
events.html: • 2019 – Naruhito ascends to the throne of Japan succeeding his father Akihito, beginning the Reiwa period.[28]

events.description: The 2024 Loblaw boycott, a Canadian boycott against retail corporation and grocer Loblaw Companies, begins.
events.html: • 2024 – The 2024 Loblaw boycott, a Canadian boycott against retail corporation and grocer Loblaw Companies, begins.[29]
